ssed, converts Signal<->SEMA), SEMA (state). Push only on success; push methods take the next engine as a parameter, sequencing Signal->Nexus->SEMA then reversing. Nexus may host an internal recursive engine for future runtime control.|] Medium VeryHigh Zero [signal-engine nexus-engine sema-engine sema signal-protocol])) (fcsg ([(Technology (Software (Distributed EventDrivenArchitecture)))] Decision [|Refines designer 476 per operator's correction. Nexus has a schema-defined decision/effect language for non-SEMA decisions — typed NexusDecision wraps Signal SemaWrite SemaRead Effect; typed NexusEffect carries side-channel variants like Stash Fanout Summarize Drop Enqueue Preempt Cascade. Generated runner loops — Nexus decides; runner executes SEMA and effect actions; completions re-enter Nexus; only NexusDecision::Signal(Output) exits to wire. Side effects are typed without pretending every side effect is already a Signal reply. The LANGUAGE existence is Maximum; the exact variant list and implementation cost remain designer-side proposals at lower magnitude pending evidence.|] Low Minimum Zero [nexus-engine sema signal-protocol schema])) (jl3k ([(Technology (Software (Distributed EventDrivenArchitecture)))] Decision [|The wire protocol is the Signal Protocol; its messages move through a universal mail mechanism (mailer/dispatcher/push system) shared by every component. Asynchronous representation lives at the data-type level: message data types themselves carry correlation IDs and lifecycle state tracking sent/queued/processing/replied transitions.|] High Medium Zero [signal-protocol mail-mechanism correlation-id])) (q73w ([(Technology (Software (Distributed EventDrivenArchitecture)))] Decision [Message lifecycle exposes hookable events: the mail dispatch system emits/commits a typed MessageSent action at the message-sent boundary, firing as soon as a message is sent so hooks, UI, observers, routers, and subscribers can react immediately.] High Medium Zero [mail-mec